ive set of life table studies ever on the mortality dynamics of a single species. He interprets the fruit fly data within the context of human aging and the aging process in general to identify the determinants of mortality. Three key themes emerge: the absence of species-specific life span limits, the context-specific nature of the mortality rate, and biodemographic linkages between longevity and reproduction. A powerful foundation for the emerging field of biodemography and a rich framework for considering the future of human life span, Longevity will be an indispensable resource for readers from a range of fields including population biology, demography, gerontology, ecology, evolutionary biology, and medical research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aLongevity. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Biology.2bisacsh  aAgeing.  aAmphibian.  aBacteria.  aBaseline Study.  aBehavior.  aBiodemography.  aBiological system.  aBiologist.  aBiology.  aBiomedicine.  aBrain size.  aCentenarian.  aCeratitis capitata.  aCeteris paribus.  aCoevolution.  aConfidence interval.  aCorrelation coefficient.  aDegenerative disease.  aDemographic dividend.  aDemography.  aDisease.  aDrosophila melanogaster.  aDrosophila.  aEcology.  aEgg as food.  aEmergence.  aEnvironmental factor.  aEstimation.  aEusociality.  aEvolution.  aEvolutionary biology.  aExtrapolation.  aFecundity.  aFemale.  aFertility.  aGerm cell.  aGerontology.  aGrandparent.  aHeritability.  aHibernation.  aHominidae.  aHomo erectus.  aHomo habilis.  aHomo sapiens.  aHousefly.  aHydrolysate.  aInsect.  aInvertebrate.  aJames Vaupel.  aJeanne Calment.  aKin selection.  aLarva.  aLate-life mortality deceleration.  aLeveling (philosophy).  aLife expectancy.  aLife history 